Niklas Hjalmarsson, defenseman for the Chicago Blackhawks, took a puck to the throat in the first period of Game 2 in the Blackhawks/Wild series Sunday night.  He laid on the ice for a few minutes, after which time he skated back to the bench, was examined by the medical staff, and returned to play.  

Tonight, although he is physically unable to speak because of the shot to the neck he took two days ago, he is lacing up his skates for Game 3.

I'm a Red Wings fan; I hate anything that resembles the Chicago Blackhawks.  However, my hat is off to Hjalmarsson for his toughness.

Playoff hockey, and the men that play it, are unequivocally badass.

The game has evolved. The number of sports related traumatic brain injuries, most classified as concussions, continues to grow each year. But, these head injuries don't just happen in major contact sports like football. Athletes who are participating in sports like basketball, cycling, rugby, soccer, motor sports, skateboarding, and baseball are all seeing the number of these injuries increase substantially each year. Our goal as a brand is to bring a heightened level of awareness about sports related traumatic brain injuries to today's athlete. The game of sports is now a game of performance, "grey matter", and awareness. www.protectyourskull.com

Last night the NY Rangers won the Eastern Conference Finals and are going to fight for Lord Stanley's Cup for the first time in 20 years (they won it in '94)!!! I was trying to think of the ups and downs the team has faced this year, and how to explain it to non-hockey people. Best I could think of was the Avengers. We have our black widow in Mats Zuccarello, our Hawkeye in Martin St. Louis (who lost his mother in the middle of the playoffs, RIP), our Iron Man in Rick Nash, our Captain America in Ryan McDonagh, and... for when you bring an army, we have our Hulk  in Henrik Lundqvist. We had the worst start to the season imaginable, but have become a tough, resilient and feisty team, and god damn, I believe we can win!!!

TL:DR? I haven't missed a single game in the last 6 years and LETS GO RANGERS!!!!

Niklas Hjalmarsson, defenseman for the Chicago Blackhawks, took a puck to the throat in the first period of Game 2 in the Blackhawks/Wild series Sunday night.  He laid on the ice for a few minutes, after which time he skated back to the bench, was examined by the medical staff, and returned to play.  

Tonight, although he is physically unable to speak because of the shot to the neck he took two days ago, he is lacing up his skates for Game 3.

I'm a Red Wings fan; I hate anything that resembles the Chicago Blackhawks.  However, my hat is off to Hjalmarsson for his toughness.

Playoff hockey, and the men that play it, are unequivocally badass.
